free_txt: Averaged values.
Experiment description.
Numerical values on tape.
45 MeV Harwell electron linear accel.
Comment added.
Comment adapted to EXFOR.
From NEUDADA.
Date is corrected. Redundant HISTORY in
SAN 002 - 006 erased
Last corrections have been done - SM
SD: ASSUMED was added in Subent 002.
.Measured transmission, fission neutron yield and
neutron spectrum.
.Sigma(total) derived from transmission.
.Eta derived from transmission, yield (corrected for
single elastic scattering) and the neutron spectrum.
.Sigma(fission) derived from normalized ETA and
sigma(total) using    sigma(fission) =
eta*(sigma(total)-sigma(scattering))/nu-bar(prompt),
assuming nu-bar(prompt) = 2.864 (constant) and taking
for sigma(scattering) an estimate based on resonance
parameters (BNL-325,2nd ed,Suppl.2 and KFK-120/1/1V3)
and on sigma(potential) = 10.3+-0.5 b (C.A.Uttley,
EANDC(UK)-40 l ,unpublished).
.Background subtracted using black resonance technique.
Permanent resonance filters are
low energy run  sodium, high energy run  aluminium.
.Corrected for single elastic scattering in sample
(high Z), sample impurities (low Z)  and in the
aluminium windows of the sample container.
Liquid scintillator with pulse shape
discrimination against gamma radiation for fission
yield measurements, boron-10 slab viewed by Na-I
crystals for neutron spectrum measurements and
Lithium loaded glass detectors for both
neutron spectrum measurements and transmission
measurements.
45 MeV Harwell electron linear accel.
Photo neutrons from booster target used,
neutron pulse width (immoderated) = 220 ns.
Time of flight paths = 97.55 m and 34.9 m,
timing channel width = 125 ns.
Normalized between 65.39 eV and
65.94 eV to ETA = 1.547+-3% which was found
by the low energy measurement.
.This measurement was normalized at 10.95 eV to ETA =
2.041 (F.D.Brooks et al.,AERE-M-1709(1966)),
.which itself has been normalized at thermal energy.
.Sigma(fission) has been normalized through eta.
Three samples of 2.9 inch diameter contained in
3.0 inch diameter 12 inch long aluminum cylinders.
Uncertainty includes:
.Statistical errors 3% in the peaks and
at the high energy end of the spectrum, 100% in the
valleys at the low energy end, after subtraction of
background,
.Uncertainty in the resonance part of sigma(scattering)
(assumed to be 50%)  gives an error of less
than 4% in the result,
.Errors due to multiple in stead of single scattering
a few per cent,
.Errors in background subtraction which only in regions
with sigma(fission) less than 10 b  will exceed  3%,
.The normalization of the high energy experiment is
done in a region where the error on ETA is 3%.
Fission neutrons.
Schomberg 1968-10.

.Errors in background subtraction which only in regions

.The normalization of the high energy experiment is
done in a region where the error on ETA is 3 per cent.
.A total error of 5 per cent is estimated.
